{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":7765,"text":"(Music)"},{"time":142825,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":145924,"text":"Thank you very much. (Applause)"},{"time":151284,"text":"Thank you. It's a distinct privilege to be here."}]},{"cues":[{"time":154957,"text":"A few weeks ago, I saw a video on YouTube"},{"time":156881,"text":"of Congresswoman Gabrielle Giffords"},{"time":159161,"text":"at the early stages of her recovery"},{"time":161320,"text":"from one of those awful bullets."},{"time":163505,"text":"This one entered her left hemisphere, and"},{"time":165626,"text":"knocked out her Broca's area, the speech center of her brain."},{"time":169142,"text":"And in this session, Gabby's working with a speech therapist,"},{"time":173048,"text":"and she's struggling to produce"},{"time":174837,"text":"some of the most basic words, and you can see her"},{"time":177949,"text":"growing more and more devastated, until she ultimately"},{"time":181128,"text":"breaks down into sobbing tears, and she starts sobbing"},{"time":184004,"text":"wordlessly into the arms of her therapist."},{"time":187980,"text":"And after a few moments, her therapist tries a new tack,"},{"time":190297,"text":"and they start singing together,"},{"time":191932,"text":"and Gabby starts to sing through her tears,"},{"time":194073,"text":"and you can hear her clearly able to enunciate"},{"time":196736,"text":"the words to a song that describe the way she feels,"},{"time":199197,"text":"and she sings, in one descending scale, she sings,"},{"time":202117,"text":"\"Let it shine, let it shine, let it shine.\""},{"time":205726,"text":"And it's a very powerful and poignant reminder of how"},{"time":208707,"text":"the beauty of music has the ability to speak"},{"time":212271,"text":"where words fail, in this case literally speak."}]},{"cues":[{"time":217047,"text":"Seeing this video of Gabby Giffords reminded me"},{"time":218800,"text":"of the work of Dr. Gottfried Schlaug,"},{"time":221601,"text":"one of the preeminent neuroscientists studying music and the brain at Harvard,"},{"time":225352,"text":"and Schlaug is a proponent of a therapy called"},{"time":227771,"text":"Melodic Intonation Therapy, which has become very popular in music therapy now."},{"time":232784,"text":"Schlaug found that his stroke victims who were aphasic,"},{"time":237107,"text":"could not form sentences of three- or four-word sentences,"},{"time":241757,"text":"but they could still sing the lyrics to a song,"},{"time":245060,"text":"whether it was \"Happy Birthday To You\""},{"time":247009,"text":"or their favorite song by the Eagles or the Rolling Stones."},{"time":249647,"text":"And after 70 hours of intensive singing lessons,"},{"time":252586,"text":"he found that the music was able to literally rewire"},{"time":256588,"text":"the brains of his patients and create a homologous"},{"time":259040,"text":"speech center in their right hemisphere"},{"time":260932,"text":"to compensate for the left hemisphere's damage."}]},{"cues":[{"time":264431,"text":"When I was 17, I visited Dr. Schlaug's lab, and in one afternoon"},{"time":267816,"text":"he walked me through some of the leading research"},{"time":270332,"text":"on music and the brain -- how musicians had"},{"time":274167,"text":"fundamentally different brain structure than non-musicians,"},{"time":277231,"text":"how music, and listening to music,"},{"time":278741,"text":"could just light up the entire brain, from"},{"time":280995,"text":"our prefrontal cortex all the way back to our cerebellum,"},{"time":284469,"text":"how music was becoming a neuropsychiatric modality"},{"time":287296,"text":"to help children with autism, to help people struggling"},{"time":290919,"text":"with stress and anxiety and depression,"},{"time":293704,"text":"how deeply Parkinsonian patients would find that their tremor"},{"time":297119,"text":"and their gait would steady when they listened to music,"},{"time":300500,"text":"and how late-stage Alzheimer's patients, whose dementia"},{"time":303909,"text":"was so far progressed that they could no longer recognize"},{"time":306805,"text":"their family, could still pick out a tune by Chopin"},{"time":309591,"text":"at the piano that they had learned when they were children."}]},{"cues":[{"time":313253,"text":"But I had an ulterior motive of visiting Gottfried Schlaug,"},{"time":316300,"text":"and it was this: that I was at a crossroads in my life,"},{"time":319518,"text":"trying to choose between music and medicine."},{"time":322303,"text":"I had just completed my undergraduate, and I was working"},{"time":325264,"text":"as a research assistant at the lab of Dennis Selkoe,"},{"time":328137,"text":"studying Parkinson's disease at Harvard, and I had fallen"},{"time":331600,"text":"in love with neuroscience. I wanted to become a surgeon."},{"time":334467,"text":"I wanted to become a doctor like Paul Farmer or Rick Hodes,"},{"time":338245,"text":"these kind of fearless men who go into places like Haiti or Ethiopia"},{"time":342362,"text":"and work with AIDS patients with multidrug-resistant"},{"time":345193,"text":"tuberculosis, or with children with disfiguring cancers."},{"time":348982,"text":"I wanted to become that kind of Red Cross doctor,"},{"time":351906,"text":"that doctor without borders."},{"time":353910,"text":"On the other hand, I had played the violin my entire life."}]},{"cues":[{"time":357453,"text":"Music for me was more than a passion. It was obsession."},{"time":361195,"text":"It was oxygen. I was lucky enough to have studied"},{"time":364358,"text":"at the Juilliard School in Manhattan, and to have played"},{"time":367437,"text":"my debut with Zubin Mehta and the Israeli philharmonic orchestra in Tel Aviv,"},{"time":371792,"text":"and it turned out that Gottfried Schlaug"},{"time":373830,"text":"had studied as an organist at the Vienna Conservatory,"},{"time":377054,"text":"but had given up his love for music to pursue a career"},{"time":379437,"text":"in medicine. And that afternoon, I had to ask him,"},{"time":383118,"text":"\"How was it for you making that decision?\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":385654,"text":"And he said that there were still times when he wished"},{"time":387683,"text":"he could go back and play the organ the way he used to,"},{"time":390455,"text":"and that for me, medical school could wait,"},{"time":393672,"text":"but that the violin simply would not."},{"time":396447,"text":"And after two more years of studying music, I decided"},{"time":399007,"text":"to shoot for the impossible before taking the MCAT"},{"time":401816,"text":"and applying to medical school like a good Indian son"},{"time":404392,"text":"to become the next Dr. Gupta. (Laughter)"},{"time":407250,"text":"And I decided to shoot for the impossible and I took"},{"time":409882,"text":"an audition for the esteemed Los Angeles Philharmonic."},{"time":412825,"text":"It was my first audition, and after three days of playing"},{"time":415827,"text":"behind a screen in a trial week, I was offered the position."},{"time":418853,"text":"And it was a dream. It was a wild dream to perform"},{"time":422771,"text":"in an orchestra, to perform in the iconic Walt Disney Concert Hall"},{"time":426271,"text":"in an orchestra conducted now by the famous Gustavo Dudamel,"},{"time":429855,"text":"but much more importantly to me to be surrounded"},{"time":432841,"text":"by musicians and mentors that became my new family,"},{"time":436731,"text":"my new musical home."}]},{"cues":[{"time":439925,"text":"But a year later, I met another musician who had also"},{"time":443635,"text":"studied at Juilliard, one who profoundly helped me"},{"time":446724,"text":"find my voice and shaped my identity as a musician."},{"time":451082,"text":"Nathaniel Ayers was a double bassist at Juilliard, but"},{"time":454363,"text":"he suffered a series of psychotic episodes in his early 20s,"},{"time":458102,"text":"was treated with thorazine at Bellevue,"},{"time":460448,"text":"and ended up living homeless on the streets of Skid Row"},{"time":463924,"text":"in downtown Los Angeles 30 years later."},{"time":466370,"text":"Nathaniel's story has become a beacon for homelessness"},{"time":469815,"text":"and mental health advocacy throughout the United States,"},{"time":472673,"text":"as told through the book and the movie \"The Soloist,\""},{"time":474818,"text":"but I became his friend, and I became his violin teacher,"},{"time":477964,"text":"and I told him that wherever he had his violin,"},{"time":480474,"text":"and wherever I had mine, I would play a lesson with him."}]},{"cues":[{"time":483445,"text":"And on the many times I saw Nathaniel on Skid Row,"},{"time":486124,"text":"I witnessed how music was able to bring him back"},{"time":488933,"text":"from his very darkest moments, from what seemed to me"},{"time":491900,"text":"in my untrained eye to be"},{"time":493860,"text":"the beginnings of a schizophrenic episode."},{"time":497660,"text":"Playing for Nathaniel, the music took on a deeper meaning,"},{"time":500914,"text":"because now it was about communication,"},{"time":503472,"text":"a communication where words failed, a communication"},{"time":506382,"text":"of a message that went deeper than words, that registered"},{"time":509540,"text":"at a fundamentally primal level in Nathaniel's psyche,"},{"time":513029,"text":"yet came as a true musical offering from me."},{"time":517576,"text":"I found myself growing outraged that someone"},{"time":521553,"text":"like Nathaniel could have ever been homeless on Skid Row"},{"time":525462,"text":"because of his mental illness, yet how many tens of thousands"},{"time":528801,"text":"of others there were out there on Skid Row alone"},{"time":531906,"text":"who had stories as tragic as his, but were never going to have a book or a movie"},{"time":536662,"text":"made about them that got them off the streets?"},{"time":538924,"text":"And at the very core of this crisis of mine, I felt somehow"},{"time":542937,"text":"the life of music had chosen me, where somehow,"},{"time":547032,"text":"perhaps possibly in a very naive sense, I felt what Skid Row"},{"time":550001,"text":"really needed was somebody like Paul Farmer"},{"time":553012,"text":"and not another classical musician playing on Bunker Hill."}]},{"cues":[{"time":557153,"text":"But in the end, it was Nathaniel who showed me"},{"time":559203,"text":"that if I was truly passionate about change,"},{"time":561930,"text":"if I wanted to make a difference, I already had the perfect instrument to do it,"},{"time":566253,"text":"that music was the bridge that connected my world and his."}]},{"cues":[{"time":571022,"text":"There's a beautiful quote"},{"time":572694,"text":"by the Romantic German composer Robert Schumann,"},{"time":575158,"text":"who said, \"To send light into the darkness of men's hearts,"},{"time":580367,"text":"such is the duty of the artist.\""},{"time":582792,"text":"And this is a particularly poignant quote"},{"time":585228,"text":"because Schumann himself suffered from schizophrenia"},{"time":587967,"text":"and died in asylum."},{"time":590075,"text":"And inspired by what I learned from Nathaniel,"},{"time":592537,"text":"I started an organization on Skid Row of musicians"},{"time":594901,"text":"called Street Symphony, bringing the light of music"},{"time":598094,"text":"into the very darkest places, performing"},{"time":600738,"text":"for the homeless and mentally ill at shelters and clinics"},{"time":603325,"text":"on Skid Row, performing for combat veterans"},{"time":607355,"text":"with post-traumatic stress disorder, and for the incarcerated"},{"time":610765,"text":"and those labeled as criminally insane."}]},{"cues":[{"time":614569,"text":"After one of our events at the Patton State Hospital"},{"time":616962,"text":"in San Bernardino, a woman walked up to us"},{"time":619483,"text":"and she had tears streaming down her face,"},{"time":621800,"text":"and she had a palsy, she was shaking,"},{"time":624266,"text":"and she had this gorgeous smile, and she said"},{"time":627288,"text":"that she had never heard classical music before,"},{"time":629270,"text":"she didn't think she was going to like it, she had never"},{"time":631696,"text":"heard a violin before, but that hearing this music was like hearing the sunshine,"},{"time":635798,"text":"and that nobody ever came to visit them, and that for the first time in six years,"},{"time":639167,"text":"when she heard us play, she stopped shaking without medication."}]},{"cues":[{"time":643970,"text":"Suddenly, what we're finding with these concerts,"},{"time":646928,"text":"away from the stage, away from the footlights, out"},{"time":649970,"text":"of the tuxedo tails, the musicians become the conduit"},{"time":653591,"text":"for delivering the tremendous therapeutic benefits"},{"time":656713,"text":"of music on the brain to an audience that would never"},{"time":659806,"text":"have access to this room,"},{"time":661608,"text":"would never have access to the kind of music that we make."},{"time":667440,"text":"Just as medicine serves to heal more"},{"time":670871,"text":"than the building blocks of the body alone,"},{"time":674169,"text":"the power and beauty of music transcends the \"E\""},{"time":677936,"text":"in the middle of our beloved acronym."},{"time":680671,"text":"Music transcends the aesthetic beauty alone."},{"time":684309,"text":"The synchrony of emotions that we experience when we"},{"time":687319,"text":"hear an opera by Wagner, or a symphony by Brahms,"},{"time":690576,"text":"or chamber music by Beethoven, compels us to remember"},{"time":694222,"text":"our shared, common humanity, the deeply communal"},{"time":698130,"text":"connected consciousness, the empathic consciousness"},{"time":701545,"text":"that neuropsychiatrist Iain McGilchrist says is hard-wired"},{"time":705118,"text":"into our brain's right hemisphere."},{"time":708194,"text":"And for those living in the most dehumanizing conditions"},{"time":711590,"text":"of mental illness within homelessness"},{"time":713751,"text":"and incarceration, the music and the beauty of music"},{"time":716534,"text":"offers a chance for them to transcend the world around them,"},{"time":721166,"text":"to remember that they still have the capacity to experience"},{"time":724548,"text":"something beautiful and that humanity has not forgotten them."},{"time":728500,"text":"And the spark of that beauty, the spark of that humanity"},{"time":731361,"text":"transforms into hope,"},{"time":734161,"text":"and we know, whether we choose the path of music"},{"time":737121,"text":"or of medicine, that's the very first thing we must instill"},{"time":740330,"text":"within our communities, within our audiences,"},{"time":742269,"text":"if we want to inspire healing from within."}]},{"cues":[{"time":746200,"text":"I'd like to end with a quote by John Keats,"},{"time":748876,"text":"the Romantic English poet,"},{"time":750921,"text":"a very famous quote that I'm sure all of you know."},{"time":753859,"text":"Keats himself had also given up a career in medicine"},{"time":756878,"text":"to pursue poetry, but he died when he was a year older than me."},{"time":760199,"text":"And Keats said, \"Beauty is truth, and truth beauty."},{"time":765272,"text":"That is all ye know on Earth, and all ye need to know.\""},{"time":774527,"text":"(Music)"},{"time":938650,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}